{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493314"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:05:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:05:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1281"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1281"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.03,0.01,0.78,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86834"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1281","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1281"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1281"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71107"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"141"},{"type":"tags","id":"2793"},{"type":"tags","id":"3874"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3308"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5659"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29825"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42276"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86834"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her bone mineral density results. She has no significant symptoms and no history of fractures. She has a medical history of rheumatoid arthritis treated with methotrexate, folic acid, and prednisolone 20mg daily for the past 18 months. She takes vitamin D and calcium supplements. She reached menopause at age 51 and did not undergo hormone replacement therapy. She drinks one standard alcoholic drink most nights and smokes 10 cigarettes daily. Her diet is vegetarian with three serves of dairy per day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 19 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. A dual-energy X-ray absorptiometry (DEXA) scan reveals a T-score of -2.8 (\u2264-2.5) and Z-score of -3.0 (\u2264-2.5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate pharmacological management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["No additional therapy","Hormone replacement therapy","Strontium ranelate","Bisphosphonate","Denosumab"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has osteoporosis based on her T-score of -2.8. Her Z-score of -3.0 suggests significant secondary osteoporosis, which in this case is likely due to rheumatoid arthritis and significant glucocorticoid use. Additional risk factors for osteoporosis in this case include post-menopausal status without hormone replacement therapy, smoking, and low BMI.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBisphosphonate\u003C/strong\u003E therapy is the most appropriate first-line treatment for glucocorticoid-induced osteoporosis. These medications can be administered orally or intravenously and have proven efficacy in fracture prevention in both primary and secondary osteoporosis. They are cost-effective and allow for drug holidays after several years of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Edenosumab\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective alternative osteoporosis agent administered subcutaneously every six months, it is not first-line for glucocorticoid-induced osteoporosis where bisphosphonates have stronger evidence and are preferred. Additionally, denosumab requires indefinite continuation due to the rebound increased risk of vertebral fractures upon cessation, making it less favourable in younger patients such as this 60-year-old woman.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHormone replacement therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is only appropriate for women under 60 years within five years of menopause. This patient is outside this window and would not be suitable given the associated cardiovascular and breast cancer risks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStrontium ranelate\u003C/strong\u003E is no longer available in Australia due to risks of venous thromboembolism and severe cutaneous reactions. It was previously used only when other treatments were unsuitable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo additional therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate given her confirmed osteoporosis diagnosis, chronic glucocorticoid use, and multiple risk factors. Along with pharmacological therapy, she should receive counselling about smoking cessation, weight-bearing exercise, and maintaining adequate calcium intake.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Bisphosphonates are first-line therapy for both primary and glucocorticoid-induced osteoporosis.","Secondary osteoporosis is indicated by a Z-score \u2264-3.0, commonly due to rheumatoid arthritis or chronic glucocorticoid use.","Non-pharmacological management of osteoporosis includes smoking cessation, weight-bearing exercise, and adequate calcium intake."],"references":["S\u00f6zen T, \u00d6z\u0131\u015f\u0131k L, Ba\u015faran N\u00c7. An overview and management of osteoporosis. Eur J Rheumatol. 2017 Mar;4(1):46-56. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28293453/","Gambacciani M, Levancini M. Hormone replacement therapy and the prevention of postmenopausal osteoporosis. Prz Menopauzalny. 2014 Sep;13(4):213-20. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26327857/","Bell J, Blacker N, Edwards S, Frank O, Alderman C, Karan L et al. Osteoporosis. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2012;41:110-8. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/march/osteoporosis-pharmacological-prevention-and-management/","Gupta A, March L. Treating osteoporosis. Aust Prescr 2016;39:40-6. Available at: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2016.02","Marie PJ. Strontium ranelate: a dual mode of action rebalancing bone turnover in favour of bone formation. Curr Opin Rheumatol. 2006 Jun;18 Suppl 1:S11-5. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16735840/","RACGP. Strontium ranelate. In: RACGP [online]. 2017  [Accessed 20 Mar. 2022].. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/osteoporosis/recommendations/pharmacologic-approaches-to-prevention-and-treatme/strontium-ranelate"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71107"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1281"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/71107"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-24T20:09:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-24T20:33:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1281"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86834"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCou